name: PCTGFEProfessional
title: PCT Good Faith Estimate Professional
description: PCT Good Faith Estimate Professional is a profile for an professional provider to capture estimation for  items and services for the patient or, optionally, to submit to a payer (for patients using insurance). If submitting to a payer, this includes the data needed to be processed by a payer for the creation of an Advanced EOB. This profile is used for a professional GFE submission.

element.definition: A provider issued list of professional services and products which have been provided, or are to be provided, to a patient which is sent to an insurer for reimbursement.
element.comment: The Claim resource fulfills three information request requirements: Claim - a request for adjudication for reimbursement for products and/or services provided; Preauthorization - a request to authorize the future provision of products and/or services including an anticipated adjudication; and, Predetermination - a request for a non-bind adjudication of possible future products and/or services.

element.definition: Information about diagnoses relevant to the claim items.
element.comment: If the Principal Diagnosis code is known, it is important that it be shared in the GFE, particularly when the GFE is being sent to a payer for an insured patient. Payers very often need the diagnosis to be able to provide an estimate. Without the diagnosis, payers may assume the service is diagnostic and thus the patient responsibility may be higher or not covered at all than the diagnosis, such as for preventative services, would otherwise indicate. It is understood that in certain situations, such as scheduled services or GFE requests prior to orders, diagnosis is not needed or may not yet be known. However, when it is known, it is important that this information be shared to ensure the best possible estimate is provided to the patient.

element.short: Principal Diagnosis - Must Support means the information source SHALL be capable of populating and SHALL populate if available and permitted.
element.comment: If the Principal Diagnosis code is known, it is important that it be shared in the GFE, particularly when the GFE is being sent to a payer for an insured patient. Payers very often need the diagnosis to be able to provide an estimate. Without the diagnosis, payers may assume the service is diagnostic and thus the patient responsibility may be higher or not covered at all than the diagnosis, such as for preventative services, would otherwise indicate. It is understood that in certain situations, such as scheduled services or GFE requests prior to orders, diagnosis is not needed or may not yet be known. However, when it is known, it is important that this information be shared to ensure the best possible estimate is provided to the patient.
